Sorry to hear about this , if you had reported back to clinic we would have helped the best  possible . The one protocol we follow is we do follow up call for patient well being a day after.proceedure My assistant says it was unattended  by you & your family member .
As there was a pain , probably anaesthesia was preferred . Sometimes  , say  one in 100 might have solution infiltration into the facial spaces.   It results in swelling & symptoms you described , it’s called hematoma  . A known risk with posterior superior alveolar nerve block ( used for upper molar anaesthesia ) .  This is not deliberate it varies with anatomy landmarks .When such incidents occur I again repeat ,patents need. to report back to doctor & whatever the best support & help we can do will do to recover , that’s an assurance & responsibility we adhere .  I just happened to read today ,feedback  on the online forum . .  I Hope all is well ..if any issues  , you are free to report . No egos here .
